{[%evp 0,38,27,4,48,48,46,45,45,43,55,48,52,37,80,15,45,20,19,10,10,11,16,3,14,
16,-2,-11,26,10,3,-50,-33,-52,-36,-62,-62,-72,-72,-54,-64] In this chapter I
am covering two different pawn sacrifices, but, objectively speaking, only one
of them is really sound.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 (5. Bg5 {
is, in my opinion, a bit dubious, but it may be tricky in some blitz games.
After} Qb6 {White's idea is revealed by} 6. Bd3 $5 Qxd4 7. Nf3 {, to which the
critical reply is} Qg4 $1 8. Bxf5 (8. O-O $6 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 10. Nbd2 Be7 $15 {
Filippov - Solak, TUR-chT, 2014}) 8... Qxf5 {and now:} 9. O-O ({White can
start with} 9. c4 {when Black's easiest is to transpose to the main line -} e6
$5 (9... Qe4+ 10. Be3 e6 11. Nbd2 Qd3 12. Rc1 $44) 10. O-O {etc.} (10. Qb3 Qe4+
$15)) 9... e6 $5 (9... f6 {does not stop White from playing} 10. c4 $5 {
As far as I remember, I lost a few online blitz games when facing this
dangerous piece sacrifice, after} fxg5 11. cxd5 $44 {White has the initiative,
S. Mareco - S. Panda, Dubai, 2022}) 10. c4 Nd7 11. Nc3 Be7 $1 {A key move in
Black's set-up, it is important to neutralize the annoying bishop. After} 12.
cxd5 exd5 13. Re1 Nc5 {we have arrived at the critical position:} 14. Ne2 (14.
e6 Nxe6 (14... f6 $5 15. Be3 Qd3 $132) 15. Ne2 Bxg5 16. Nxg5 Qg4 $132) 14...
Bxg5 15. Ned4 Qd3 (15... Qg6 $5 16. Nxg5 Nh6 17. e6 O-O $132) 16. Nxg5 Qxd1 17.
Raxd1 Ne7 (17... a5 $5 $132) 18. b4 Na4 19. e6 f6 20. Nf7 O-O 21. Nd6 {So far
Shevchenko - Howell, Chess24 Banter Blitz Cup, 2020, here I would like to
suggest once again} a5 $132) 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. b4 $5 {A few years
ago I wanted to play this gambit idea myself, but nowadays it cannot take by
surprise any decent theoretician. Besides, the next two Chapters are dedicated
to the possible alternatives.} Qxb4+ 8. Nd2 e6 9. Rb1 Qe7 {Now} 10. c4 {
is the most consistent move in my opinion, for a closed type of position will
favour Black.} ({To the major alternative} 10. Ne2 {Black must not hesitate
over the opportunity to lock the queenside by} b5 $1 (10... Qc7 11. c4 $36 {
J. Martinez Alcantara - E. Tian, Winter GM-B 2022}) 11. Nf3 (11. a4 a6 (11...
b4 $5) 12. Nf4 (12. axb5 $5 axb5 13. Nf3 {is probably more sound but after}
Qa7 14. Bd2 Ne7 15. Ng3 g6 16. O-O Nd7 17. Ng5 Bh6 $5 {there is no reason to
worry about}) 12... g6 $1 {is the correct way to proceed -} ({I obtained a
very good position against Martinez, but the move order was inaccurate,
because after} 12... Qc7 13. Nf3 $1 {White has objectively a very good
compensation.} (13. O-O Ne7 14. Nf3 Nf5 15. Ra1 g6 $17 {Martinez Alcantara -
Eljanov, Titled Tuesday 5th Jul, 2022}) 13... g6 14. Ng5 $44 Ne7 $140 15. Ba3)
13. Nf3 Nh6 14. c3 Nf5 15. Ne2 Bh6 $15 {and Qe7 is quite useful in both
directions - hindering the option for Bc1-a3 and keeping an eye on the h4-pawn.
}) 11... a6 $5 $146 {A pretty nice and instructive way to arrange the pieces
in the perfect way -} 12. O-O (12. a4 Qa7 $1 13. axb5 cxb5 $15) 12... Qa7 $1 {
Paradoxically enough, it turns out that this is the best square for the queen.
Moreover, Black is putting some pressure on the d4-pawn, for example} 13. Ng5
Ne7 14. Ng3 g6 $1 15. Qf3 (15. Ba3 Nd7 16. Qf3 Nf5 17. Nxf5 gxf5 18. Bxf8 Kxf8
{and it is not easy for White to prove any compensation}) 15... Nf5 $1 16. Nxf5
gxf5 {and I would prefer Black here.}) (10. Ngf3 b5 $1 11. a4 a6 12. O-O Nh6
13. g3 Nf5 14. Re1 Qc7 $15 {A. Gara - O. Girya, EU-Cup Online Final (Women)
rapid, 2020.}) 10... Nh6 11. Ne2 ({It makes sense to leave the f3-square for
the other knight rather than} 11. Ngf3 Nf5 12. O-O (12. Nf1 $5 dxc4 13. Qxc4 b5
$1 14. Qd3 Na6 $132) 12... b6 $1 13. g3 (13. cxd5 $6 cxd5 14. Ne4 Nc6 15. Neg5
Qd7 $17 {Alboredo - Fier, BRA-ch, 2022}) 13... Qb7 {and White has still to
show something in return fo the missing pawn.}) 11... Nf5 12. Nf3 (12. Ng3 $5 {
may well be White's best bet, then critical is} Nxh4 {and White has several
options to choose from. The ensuing positions are dynamically balanced, for
example} 13. Nde4 (13. Qc2 Ng6 $5 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Qc8+ Qd8 16. Qxb7 Nd7 17.
Nxh5 Rb8 18. Qxa7 Rxb1 $5 19. Nxb1 Bb4+ 20. Bd2 Bxd2+ 21. Nxd2 O-O $44) (13.
Kf1 $5 Ng6 14. Nxh5 b6 15. Nf3 Qd7 16. Bg5 c5 $1 17. Kg1 Nc6 18. dxc5 bxc5 $132
) 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Qd8 $1 15. Bg5 Qa5+ 16. Bd2 Qd8 17. Bg5 Qa5+ 18. Bd2 Qd8
19. Bg5 {?-? J. Santos - B. Martins, POR-ch, Leiria, 2022}) (12. cxd5 cxd5 {
seems to enable Black's task -} 13. Nf3 Nc6 $132) 12... dxc4 $1 {A concrete
solution to the pressure on the queenside.} ({It is a natural intention to
free Bf8 by seemingly improving the queen with} 12... Qc7 $6 {, but in fact
the latter is exposed to tactical motifs -} 13. O-O dxc4 (13... Nd7 14. cxd5
cxd5 15. Ng3 $36) 14. Qxc4 Nd7 {So far Martinez Alcantara - Moussard, Titled
Tuesday 10th May, 2022, in which White passed through} 15. d5 $1 Nxe5 $140 16.
Nxe5 Qxe5 17. dxc6 $16) 13. Qxc4 b5 14. Qd3 {It is not easy to find a proper
square for her Majesty:} ({After} 14. Qc2 Qd7 15. O-O {Black, similarly to the
main text, has} Na6 $1 {, forcing the opponent to pay attention at the jump to
the b4-square, for instance} 16. Bd2 Be7 $132) ({If} 14. Qb3 {, then} a5 $5 {
is disabling the possible break a2-a4.}) 14... Na6 $1 15. Ng3 Nxg3 16. fxg3 Nb4
17. Qe2 ({In case of} 17. Qc3 Rc8 18. O-O {the thrust} f5 $1 {is coming at the
right moment} 19. exf6 (19. Kh2 Nd5 $15) 19... gxf6 20. Kh2 Nd5 21. Qe1 Bg7
$132 {Black is about to finish development with luxury.}) 17... Qd7 18. O-O Be7
19. Kh2 a5 $132 {Black is solid enough and can rely on his queenside majority
in the long run.} *

